				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>itchyban wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">If you want to play "for fun" and have no intentions of ever, ever, ever playing a mage above elemental-level content, yes, it is a blast.
<br />

<br />
If you have even the smallest twinkling of thinking that you want to aggressively raid. Absolutely not.....</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Oh, Pooh.
<br />

<br />
Nobody just getting started and asking this question has any way to understand answers about "elemental-level content". He will need to play for quite a while before he can begin to know whether he gives a Gnoll's tail about raiding.
<br />

<br />
A mage is a great way to get that experience. You can solo, you can group, and since the PoK expansion (included in your starter kit), you can get around well enough to see the 90% of Norrath which will be yours until you hit the top end. Most importantly, it is all kinds of fun to play up to those levels. There is no telling which class will be downtrodden at that point, so don't worry about it. 
<br />

<br />
Pick a race and gender you think will be fun as your embodiment, choose no god (i.e., stay agnostic), and just do it! With your mage experience, you can quickly level up some other class later if you really want to and feel like the mage has hit a wall. At that point you'll know about pets, damage shields, all kinds of offensive magic, healing, pathing, armor/weapon effects, faction -- everything you need to make the best decision.
<br />

<br />
Which, of course, will be to keep playing the mage! <img src="images/smiles/icon_biggrin.gif" alt="Very Happy" border="0" /></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
